Here's a C++ function using the `pugixml` library for markdown to HTML conversion (note: since there's no direct C++ library for markdown to HTML conversion like Pandoc or similar tools for other languages, we'll use pugixml which can be used to parse and extract content for significant parts of markdown syntax). You would need to install pugixml via your package manager (e.g., using `sudo apt install libpugixml-dev` for Ubuntu/Debian or `pip install pugixml` for Python using `c++-pugixml` package).

```cpp
#include <pugixml.hpp>
#include <string>
#include <cctype>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown_text) {
  std::ostringstream html_stream;
  pugixml::document doc;
  pugixml::parse<0>(markdown_text.c_str(), doc, false);

  // Convert header tags
  for (pugixml::node* n = doc.first_child<pugixml::tag<1>>(); n!= nullptr; n = n->first_child()) {
    if (n->is_tag() && (n->name() == "h1" || n->name() == "h2" || n->name() == "h3" || n->name() == "h4" || n->name() == "h5" || n->name() == "h6")) {
      html_stream << "<" << n->name() << ">" << n->get<0>()(true) << "</" << n->name() << ">\n";
    } else {
      html_stream << "<" << n->name() << ">"
                  << n->get<0>(true) << "</" << n->name() << ">\n";
    }
  }

  // Convert list tags
  for (pugixml::node* n = doc.child<1>(); n!= nullptr; n = n->next_sibling<1>()) {
    if (n->is_tag() && (n->name() == "ul" || n->name() == "ol")) {
      html_stream << "<" << n->name() << ">\n";
      pugixml::node* li_node = n->first_child<1>();
      while (li_node) {
        html_stream << "<li>";
        html_stream << pugixml::to_string(*li_node);
        html_stream << "</li>\n";
        li_node = li_node->next_sibling<1>();
      }
      html_stream << "</" << n->name() << ">\n";
    }
  }

  // Convert paragraph tags
  for (pugixml::node* n = doc.child<1>(); n!= nullptr; n = n->next_sibling<1>()) {
    if (n->is_text()) {
      html_stream << "<p>" << n->get<0>()(true) << "</p>\n";
    }
  }

  return html_stream.str();
}
```

**Notes:**

1. This C++ function uses `pugixml` library to parse the markdown text and generate the HTML output. It supports header, list (unordered and ordered), and paragraph tags.
2. The function doesn't cover all possible markdown syntaxes but provides a good starting point for HTML conversion.
3. Remember to link against the `pugixml` library when building your project (`-lpugixml` for Linux or `-lPugixml` for Windows, depending on your platform).
4. If you want more comprehensive markdown support, consider using a dedicated library or external service (e.g., [marked.js](https://marked.js.org/)) to handle more complex markdown syntaxes.

