In reStructuredText (RST), URLs can be formatted using various syntaxes, depending on your needs. Here are the most common methods:

1. **Inline Links**: The simplest way to format a URL is to create an inline link. Use square brackets `[]` for the link text and parentheses `()` for the URL. For example: `[Google](https://www.google.com)`

2. **Reference Links**: If you have a list of links that appear multiple times in your document, you can define a reusable link label and use it in your text. To create a reference link, first define the label using a directive, and then use it in the text. Here's an example:

   - In your document's preamble (e.g., document.rst or conf.py):
     ```rst
    .. _google-link: https://www.google.com
     ```

   - In the text:
     ```rst
     This is a link to Google: `Google <https://<_google-link>>_`
     ```

3. **Button Links**: For styling purposes, you can use button-like links using the `:target` and CSS classes. However, this method requires some CSS customization and is less common. Here's an example:

   Create a CSS class (e.g., `button-link`):
   ```css
  .button-link {
     background-color: #4CAF50;
     color: white;
     padding: 10px 20px;
     border: none;
     text-align: center;
     text-decoration: none;
     display: inline-block;
     font-size: 16px;
     border-radius: 5px;
     transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
   }
  .button-link:hover {
     background-color: #45a049;
   }
   ```

   In the RST document:
   ```rst
   `Click me! <<https://<_your-target-url>>_ {#button-link#}`
   ```

   Then, add an HTML anchor tag with the class `button-link` to the target URL:
   ```html
   <a href="https://<_your-target-url>" class="button-link" id="button-link">Click me!</a>
   ```

Remember to replace `_your-target-url` with the actual URL and adjust the CSS class as needed.

